When the first child is born, a memento usually is awarded to the husband for 30 Austrian schillings. On obtaining employment, a second memento is presented to the woman in addition to the one awarded to the man. In principle, the couple continues to receive an allowance of 100 schillings per month per child.

During the 1970s, the structure of marriage, as nearly always happens, changed in response to economic and sociopolitical upheaval. In the 1960s, married couples with children increased, as did divorces and single mother households with children. Despite this, more and more men were living apart from their families until they married at the age of 35 or later. Cancellation notices of marriage applications were signed by the parents.
